Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["11. Key Findings", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"0016222c-b3cc-4347-8e50-9e3dd9c6a55c"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["\<\
Print[\"\\n========== KEY FINDINGS ==========\"];
Print[\"\"];
Print[\"1. LEMMA 1 PROOF VERIFICATION:\"];
Print[\"   All algebraic steps (Eq. 14 through 19) verified \
computationally.\"];
Print[\"   - Eq.(14): Total differentiation of FOC confirmed.\"];
Print[\"   - Eq.(17): Closed-form derivative expression reproduced.\"];
Print[\"   - Limit P->0: Numerator behavior matches Eq.(18).\"];
Print[\"   - Limit P->1: d(alpha)/dP proven negative (concavity argument).\"];
Print[\"\"];
Print[\"2. CRRA APPLICATION (Lemma 1(i)):\"];
Print[\"   For CRRA utility U(A) = A^(1-gamma)/(1-gamma):\"];
Print[\"   - Ra(A) = gamma/A is DARA (decreasing absolute risk aversion).\"];
Print[\"   - Lemma 1(i) holds when gamma exceeds a critical threshold.\"];
Print[\"   - Critical gamma depends on W, H, q, and the equilibrium alpha.\"];
Print[\"   - For typical parameters (W=100, H=40, q=1.3): gammaCrit ~ 1-3.\"];
Print[\"   - Most empirically relevant CRRA values (gamma=2-5) satisfy Lemma \
1(i).\"];
Print[\"\"];
Print[\"3. ECONOMIC INTERPRETATION:\"];
Print[\"   - Single-peaked demand (Lemma 1(i)) means insurers who increase \
risk\"];
Print[\"     beyond P-bar will see aggregate demand decline.\"];
Print[\"   - This creates a natural limit on risk-increasing collusion.\"];
Print[\"   - The threshold P-bar depends on consumer risk aversion.\"];
Print[\"   - Higher CRRA gamma (more risk-averse consumers) raises P-bar,\"];
Print[\"     expanding the region where risk increases boost demand.\"];
Print[\"\"];
Print[\"========== END KEY FINDINGS ==========\"];\
\>", "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[623]:=",ExpressionUUID->"456e715f-8af0-044c-8b6b-168026274a2f"],

